  "summary": "Miss Marple and Detective Inspector Claridge discuss a cheap powder box sold in Paris, though Miss Marple maintains that locating the body is the higher priority. Miss Marple expresses confidence in Lucy Ashebrooke’s capabilities and notes Lucy's professional interest in the family she serves as a housekeeper. Miss Marple also conjectures that a traveling theatre company might be relevant to the disappearance of a girl.\n\nSeparately, a young man with official credentials visits Mrs. McGillicuddy and shows her a photograph of a woman. Mrs. McGillicuddy identifies the woman as the person she saw being strangled on a train. She describes the assailant as a tall man with dark hair, likely in his thirties, though she could not see his face because he was facing away. The young man informs her that the body was found by Lucy Ashebrooke in a warehouse at Rutherford Hall, near Bramhampton. Mrs. McGillicuddy later receives a detailed letter from Miss Marple regarding these events, which makes her feel vindicated.\n\nIn a long-forgotten pigsty, Lucy and Sedrick (also referred to as Cecil or Cedric) converse. Lucy explains her professional approach to housekeeping and her enjoyment of creative tasks like cooking. Sedrick describes his minimalist, messy lifestyle in Ibiza and his aversion to meddlesome women. He discusses his family's financial situation, noting that his father lives frugally to save money from a trust established by his grandfather. Sedrick mentions that while he is a struggling painter, his brother Harold is a prominent businessman facing rumored financial problems, and he also mentions Alfred, known as \"Lightning Al.\"",
